        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He remembers the scent of bleach and stale coffee in the Fremont motel lobby. He was fourteen, watching his father under the yellow glow of the front desk lamp, his finger tracing lines in a ledger. Each number was a wall, a meal, a future. Vikram felt a swell of respect mixed with a fierce, suffocating need to escape. He didn\u2019t want to just manage the numbers; he wanted to own the entire ledger, to operate on a scale his father couldn\u2019t imagine. That night, ambition became his compass.\n\n2. The Montgomery Street office was a tomb in late 2008. Everyone else saw ruin, their faces pale in the glow of their monitors. But Vikram, presenting to the partners, felt a cold, exhilarating calm. He saw not a crash, but a generational buying opportunity. The city lights glittered below, indifferent. In that moment of collective panic, he felt his own conviction solidify into steel. He wasn't just gambling; he was executing the lesson his father's ledger taught him: in the end, real property always holds its value.\n\n3. He and Priya stood in the empty Pac Heights Victorian, dust motes dancing in the afternoon light pouring through the bay window. Outside, the bridge peeked through the fog. It was more than a house; it was a landmark of his own life, a tangible proof of the distance traveled from Fremont. Taking Priya\u2019s hand, he felt the weight of his success settle not as a burden, but as an anchor. He wasn't just working in the city anymore; he was finally, irrevocably, home.\n\n4. The memory lands like a punch: his daughter, then sixteen, on the stage for her final school debate. He was in the audience, but his attention was on his phone, closing a deal in Tokyo. He remembers looking up just as her face fell, realizing he\u2019d missed her big rebuttal. The quiet disappointment in her eyes later that evening was a debit he couldn\u2019t reconcile. That deal had made millions, but he knew, with a certainty that still chills him, that he\u2019d made a very poor trade.\n\n5. Last week, after his pre-dawn Peloton ride, the house was silent. He caught sight of a photo on the mantle: his parents, proud and tired, in front of their motel. Through the window, the dawn light hit the top of the Salesforce Tower. He felt the vast distance between those two worlds not with pride, but with a profound sense of inquiry. His parents\u2019 legacy was tangible, built with their hands. He looked at his own and wondered what would remain once the market-to-market value was stripped away."
